<body>
    <h1>Beacon Messaging Protocol</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h2 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-Background">Background</h2>
<p>The architecture for the Beacon Android SDK requires the device to broad=
cast a small data packet, referred to as the SecureID. This packet is trans=
mitted over Bluetooth using the Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) standard, and is=
 the Advertise broadcast that typically begins a GATT connection.</p>
<p>There are tight limits on the size of this packet, as well as what data =
it needs to contain.</p>
<h2 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-ProblemStatement">Problem Statement</h2>
<p>When adding data to a BLE Advertise packet, the payload cannot exceed 25=
 bytes of data. Any more than that, and the Bluetooth adapter on the device=
 fails to start broadcasting. We need to ensure that a secure ID is no more=
 than 25 bytes.</p>
<p>In addition, a SecureID needs to be a cryptographically secure payload. =
The current design is that a device provides the server with some unique id=
entifier, and the server generates several SecureIDs for the device to broa=
dcast. When these SecureIDs are given back to the device from the kiosk tha=
t picked up the broadcast, the server needs to be able to turn these back i=
nto the unique ID originally presented, be certain that the received data w=
as received by the kiosk when it was valid, and have at least some confiden=
ce that it hasn=E2=80=99t been altered or forged to prevent junk data from =
ending up in our systems.</p>
<p>SecureIDs should bear no obvious relation with each other to prevent tra=
cking a user by their Bluetooth broadcasts for extended periods of time.</p=
>
<h2 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-PayloadComponents">Payload Components</h2=
>
<p>A SecureID should contain, at minimum:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>1 byte of version data</p></li>
<li>
<p>7 bytes of unique identifier data</p></li>
<li>
<p>4 bytes of start time data</p></li>
<li>
<p>4 bytes of expire time data</p></li>
</ol>
<h2 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-ProposedSolutions:">Proposed Solutions:</=
h2>
<h3 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-AES-256-GCMEncryptedSecureID">AES-256-GCM=
 Encrypted SecureID</h3>
<p>Ciphertext contents: 1 version byte and 7 unique ID bytes</p>
<p>Plaintext contents: 8 bytes containing the start/end time, and 1 random =
byte</p>
<p>Authentication Information: 8 bytes of authentication</p>
<p>Total size: 25 bytes</p>
<h4 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-Pros:">Pros:</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Ciphertext contains the secure info, no feasible way to break AES encryp=
tion and read plaintext.</p></li>
<li>
<p>AES is highly optimized, down to the CPU level, and widely used</p></li>
<li>
<p>Because the IV contains the start/expire times, it would be easy for the=
 kiosk to filter out expired tokens itself, saving server resources</p></li=
>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-Cons:">Cons:</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Packs data into the IV, which is plaintext. This presents potential atta=
ckers info on our system and/or implementation</p></li>
<li>
<p>IV reuse can break AES encryption.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Because our IV is time-based, this is reduced, but if 2 tokens ever had =
the same IV it would be possible to break our encryption, potentially to th=
e point where the plaintext is recoverable.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Small auth tag - 8 bytes of authentication is sufficient for short-lived=
 tokens, such as the SecureIDs, but is feasible to crack and create forged =
tokens</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-AES-256-SIVEncryptedSecureID">AES-256-SIV=
 Encrypted SecureID</h3>
<p>Ciphertext contents: 1 version byte and 7 unique ID bytes</p>
<p>Plaintext contents: 8 bytes containing the start/end time, and 1 random =
byte</p>
<p>Authentication Information: 8 bytes of authentication</p>
<p>Total size: 25 bytes</p>
<h4 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-Pros:.1">Pros:</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Ciphertext contains the secure info, no feasible way to break AES encryp=
tion and read plaintext.</p></li>
<li>
<p>AES is highly optimized, down to the CPU level, and widely used</p></li>
<li>
<p>Because the IV contains the start/expire times, it would be easy for the=
 kiosk to filter out expired tokens itself, saving server resources</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>SIV mitigates the risks of reused IV data. If 2 tokens had the same IV, =
the plaintext would still not be recoverable</p></li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-Cons:.1">Cons:</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Packs data into the IV, which is plaintext. This presents potential atta=
ckers info on our system and/or implementation</p></li>
<li>
<p>Small auth tag - 8 bytes of authentication is sufficient for short-lived=
 tokens, such as the SecureIDs, but is feasible to crack and create forged =
tokens</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-XXTEAEncryptedSecureID"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XXTEA" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">XXT=
EA</a> Encrypted SecureID</h3>
<p>(Note: the algorithm <a href=3D"https://ascon.iaik.tugraz.at/" class=3D"=
external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">Ascon</a> has similar pros/cons)</p>
<p>Ciphertext contents: 1 version byte, 7 unique ID bytes, 4 start time byt=
es, 4 expire bytes</p>
<p>Authentication Information: 8 bytes of authentication</p>
<p>Total size: 24 bytes</p>
<h4 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-Pros:.2">Pros:</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Smaller payload size</p></li>
<li>
<p>Time information is not plaintext, so only the server can recover it</p>=
</li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-Cons:.2">Cons:</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p>XXTEA is not a widely used algorithm, and no standard implementation exi=
sts in Node. While there are 3rd party libraries, they are not widely used =
or thoroughly supported</p></li>
<li>
<p>Technically, XXTEA is broken encryption. However, attacks require collec=
ting many <em>billions</em> of records to be feasible</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-RaptorQTransmittedSecureID"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raptor_code" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nof=
ollow">RaptorQ</a> Transmitted SecureID</h3>
<p>RaptorQ is a type of Fountain Code encoding mechanism for transmitting a=
rbitrary data over a lossy connection without the receiver asking the sende=
r for missed packets, and without requiring a known number of packets.</p>
<p>With this, the SecureID can be arbitrarily large, but the device only br=
oadcasts 1 =E2=80=98droplet=E2=80=99 at a time. An example would be the dev=
ice has a 100 byte SecureID, it breaks it into 5 25 byte RaptorQ drops (20 =
bytes of data, 5 bytes of overhead), and broadcasts them round-robin until =
the secureID expires. Each droplet is broadcast for, say, 1 second, so a us=
er would have to be near a kiosk for ~6 seconds before it has collected eno=
ugh drops to decode the message.</p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file=
-wrapper image-center-wrapper confluence-embedded-manual-size"><img class=
=3D"confluence-embedded-image image-center" alt=3D"image-20241114-203807.pn=
g" width=3D"468" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"42ab7d99692c009f6b8ded034ab852b6e6=
6fc4e8652c9d5ba08cbe109b2f7791" data-image-src=3D"https://t-ads.atlassian.n=
et/wiki/download/attachments/3466297346/image-20241114-203807.png?version=
=3D1&amp;modificationDate=3D1731616689786&amp;cacheVersion=3D1&amp;api=3Dv2=
" data-height=3D"346" data-width=3D"714" data-unresolved-comment-count=3D"0=
" data-linked-resource-id=3D"3466493976" data-linked-resource-version=3D"1"=
 data-linked-resource-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-default-alia=
s=3D"image-20241114-203807.png" data-base-url=3D"https://t-ads.atlassian.ne=
t/wiki" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" data-linked-resourc=
e-container-id=3D"3466297346" data-linked-resource-container-version=3D"1" =
data-media-id=3D"91058473-23c5-4bbf-80a7-7febc9ca9f50" data-media-type=3D"f=
ile" height=3D"226"></span>
<h4 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-Pros:.3">Pros:</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Essentially no limitation on size of SecureID, allowing much more data t=
o be transmitted while maintaining high security</p></li>
<li>
<p>Even smaller chance of tracking a user via their Bluetooth broadcasts, a=
s the data being broadcasts will change more frequently than their SecureID=
 will.</p></li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"BeaconMessagingProtocol-Cons:.3">Cons:</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Licensing limitations. RaptorQ is patented by Qualcomm, and use requires=
 a license. Qualcomm has stated that they will only enforce their patents f=
or devices that are wide-area wireless devices, which we would not run afou=
l of for Beacon. Additionally, this may no longer be the case as several FO=
SS libraries implement it.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Limited library support</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>There are only 2 libraries that support RaptorQ encoding/decoding:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><a href=3D"https://crates.io/crates/raptorq" class=3D"external-link" rel=
=3D"nofollow">https://crates.io/crates/raptorq</a> (Rust)</p></li>
<li>
<p><a href=3D"https://openrq-team.github.io/openrq/" data-card-appearance=
=3D"inline" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">https://openrq-team.gi=
thub.io/openrq/</a> (Java)</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>The Rust version is actively developed, but would be difficult to integr=
ate into Android code, and the Java version has effectively been abandoned =
since 2015.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Puts a lower-bound on how long a user can be near a kiosk before we can =
determine their SecureID</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Some mitigation by configuring how long a single droplet is broadcast</p=
></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Extra complexity on both the sender and receiver</p></li>
</ul>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
